[
    {
        "content": "<p><a href=\"/user_uploads/3121/NsrGTW1r1A9MBe3K7ps3HXi5/image.png\">image.png</a></p>\n<div class=\"message_inline_image\"><a href=\"/user_uploads/3121/NsrGTW1r1A9MBe3K7ps3HXi5/image.png\" title=\"image.png\"><img data-original-content-type=\"image/png\" data-original-dimensions=\"648x256\" src=\"/user_uploads/thumbnail/3121/NsrGTW1r1A9MBe3K7ps3HXi5/image.png/840x560.webp\"></a></div><div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kn\">import</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Mathlib</span>\n<span class=\"kn\">open</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">ZMod</span>\n<span class=\"sd\">/--6. Solve the simultaneous congruences</span>\n<span class=\"sd\">$$</span>\n<span class=\"sd\">\\begin{aligned}</span>\n\n<span class=\"sd\">x &amp; \\equiv 1(\\bmod 2) \\\\</span>\n\n<span class=\"sd\">x &amp; \\equiv 6(\\bmod 7) \\\\</span>\n\n<span class=\"sd\">x &amp; \\equiv 2(\\bmod 27) \\\\</span>\n\n<span class=\"sd\">x &amp; \\equiv 6(\\bmod 11)</span>\n\n<span class=\"sd\">\\end{aligned}</span>\n<span class=\"sd\">$$-/</span>\n<span class=\"c1\">-- Step 1 Function to compute the modular inverse of `a` modulo `m`</span>\n<span class=\"kn\">def</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">modInverse</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">a</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">m</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Nat</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Option</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Nat</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"k\">let</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">g</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Nat</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">gcd</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">a</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">m</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"k\">if</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">g</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">1</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">then</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"c1\">-- Use extended Euclidean algorithm to find the inverse</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"k\">let</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"o\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">_</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Nat</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">xgcd</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">a</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">m</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"c1\">-- Ensure the result is a natural number in [0, m-1]</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"n\">some</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">Nat</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">mod</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">Int</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">toNat</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">%</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">m</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">+</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">m</span><span class=\"o\">))</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">m</span><span class=\"o\">)</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"k\">else</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"n\">none</span>\n\n<span class=\"c1\">-- Step 2 Function to solve the system of congruences using CRT</span>\n<span class=\"kn\">def</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">solveCRT</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">moduli</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">residues</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">List</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Nat</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Option</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Nat</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"k\">let</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">M</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">moduli</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">prod</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"c1\">-- Compute the solution using CRT</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"k\">let</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">result</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">residues</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">zip</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">moduli</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">|&gt;.</span><span class=\"n\">foldlM</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"k\">fun</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">acc</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">r</span><span class=\"o\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">m</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">=&gt;</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"k\">let</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Mi</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">M</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">/</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">m</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"k\">match</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">modInverse</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Mi</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">m</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">with</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"bp\">|</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">some</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">yi</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">=&gt;</span>\n<span class=\"w\">      </span><span class=\"c1\">-- Compute the term and ensure it remains a natural number</span>\n<span class=\"w\">      </span><span class=\"k\">let</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">term</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">r</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">*</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Mi</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">*</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">yi</span>\n<span class=\"w\">      </span><span class=\"n\">pure</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">acc</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">+</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">term</span><span class=\"o\">)</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"bp\">|</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">none</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">=&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">none</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"c1\">-- Modular inverse doesn't exist</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">0</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"k\">match</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">result</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">with</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"bp\">|</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">some</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">=&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">some</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">%</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">M</span><span class=\"o\">)</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"bp\">|</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">none</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">=&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">none</span>\n\n<span class=\"c1\">-- Step 3 Define the moduli and residues</span>\n<span class=\"kn\">def</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">moduli</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">List</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Nat</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"mi\">2</span><span class=\"o\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">7</span><span class=\"o\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">27</span><span class=\"o\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">11</span><span class=\"o\">]</span>\n<span class=\"kn\">def</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">residues</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">List</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Nat</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"mi\">1</span><span class=\"o\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">6</span><span class=\"o\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">2</span><span class=\"o\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">6</span><span class=\"o\">]</span>\n\n<span class=\"c1\">-- Step 4 Solve the system of congruences</span>\n<span class=\"kn\">def</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">solution</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Option</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Nat</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"n\">solveCRT</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">moduli</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">residues</span>\n\n<span class=\"c1\">-- Step 5 Print the special solution</span>\n<span class=\"bp\">#</span><span class=\"n\">eval</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">solution</span>\n\n<span class=\"c1\">-- Step 6 Check the condition of the CRT theorem</span>\n<span class=\"bp\">#</span><span class=\"n\">eval</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"mi\">2</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Nat</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">Coprime</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">7</span>\n<span class=\"bp\">#</span><span class=\"n\">eval</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"mi\">2</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Nat</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">Coprime</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">27</span>\n<span class=\"bp\">#</span><span class=\"n\">eval</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"mi\">2</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Nat</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">Coprime</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">11</span>\n<span class=\"bp\">#</span><span class=\"n\">eval</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"mi\">7</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Nat</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">Coprime</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">27</span>\n<span class=\"bp\">#</span><span class=\"n\">eval</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"mi\">7</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Nat</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">Coprime</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">1</span>\n<span class=\"bp\">#</span><span class=\"n\">eval</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"mi\">27</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Nat</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">Coprime</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">11</span>\n<span class=\"bp\">#</span><span class=\"n\">eval</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">2</span><span class=\"bp\">*</span><span class=\"mi\">7</span><span class=\"bp\">*</span><span class=\"mi\">27</span><span class=\"bp\">*</span><span class=\"mi\">11</span>\n<span class=\"c1\">-- Thus by the CRT theorem, the unique soulution is $x \\equiv 83 (\\bmod M)$, where $M=2 × 7 × 27 × 11 = 4158$.</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>I hope to be able to show that (83: ZMod 4158) is the only solution of the above congruent equation in the congruent sense, and I do not know how to give a formal proof. Can someone help me?</p>",
        "id": 512544211,
        "sender_full_name": "Move fast",
        "timestamp": 1744807545
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>It seems you want to use the Chinese Remainder Theorem. Can you state that? (Or, if you're willing to use the mathlib version: what does it say?) Have you tried using that theorem?</p>",
        "id": 512545272,
        "sender_full_name": "Michael Rothgang",
        "timestamp": 1744807846
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Or is your question rather \"how do I prove a theorem\" (as opposed to making a definition)?</p>",
        "id": 512545320,
        "sender_full_name": "Michael Rothgang",
        "timestamp": 1744807865
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Perhaps, the first step: can you state the result you want to prove in Lean? You won't be able to prove it in Lean otherwise :-)</p>",
        "id": 512545436,
        "sender_full_name": "Michael Rothgang",
        "timestamp": 1744807898
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I want to show that (83: ZMod 4158) is the only solution of the above congruent equation in the congruent sense, but I don't know how to use the Chinese Remainder Theorem in Mathlib.</p>",
        "id": 512545901,
        "sender_full_name": "Move fast",
        "timestamp": 1744808030
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>If you can give me a Lean's proof to solve the following question, maybe I will know how to prove the more complex situation. </p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"TeX\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"k\">\\begin</span><span class=\"nb\">{</span>aligned<span class=\"nb\">}</span>\n\nx <span class=\"nb\">&amp;</span> <span class=\"k\">\\equiv</span> 1(<span class=\"k\">\\bmod</span> 2) <span class=\"k\">\\\\</span>\n\nx <span class=\"nb\">&amp;</span> <span class=\"k\">\\equiv</span> 6(<span class=\"k\">\\bmod</span> 7) <span class=\"k\">\\\\</span>\n\n<span class=\"k\">\\end</span><span class=\"nb\">{</span>aligned<span class=\"nb\">}</span>\n</code></pre></div>",
        "id": 512548140,
        "sender_full_name": "Move fast",
        "timestamp": 1744808592
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>You still haven't stated the result yet :)</p>",
        "id": 512548485,
        "sender_full_name": "Aaron Liu",
        "timestamp": 1744808697
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>There are many ways to say this in Lean.</p>",
        "id": 512548539,
        "sender_full_name": "Aaron Liu",
        "timestamp": 1744808715
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The result is (83: ZMod 4158), that is to say $x \\equiv 83 (\\bmod 4158)$. I want to show that is the unique solution by the Chinese Remainder Theorem.</p>",
        "id": 512549141,
        "sender_full_name": "Move fast",
        "timestamp": 1744808880
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I think Aaron is asking for a statement in Lean</p>",
        "id": 512550094,
        "sender_full_name": "Michał Mrugała",
        "timestamp": 1744809124
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Maybe like (83: ZMod 4158), if we can get the result like this</p>",
        "id": 512550806,
        "sender_full_name": "Move fast",
        "timestamp": 1744809321
    },
    {
